feedback: I used my first instinct by what I observed on the sample images,
Any face that had two or more features I would categorize as family 1. Any face that had a single feature I would categorize as family 2.
It seemed like Family 2 had more combinations with eyes.
I didn't really notice any patterns... it was confusing and hard since it was 100 of them...
I just tried to remember what the most common associations from the training were.
I tryed to think of them as a face.

I looked at the original hundred and noticed that only one feature usually meant it was in family 2. But then that rule was broken several times, but not all. I mostly went with my gut and followed that rule 90% of the time and the other 10% I went against the rule, just like the original set did.
I just tried to absorb which combinations of features occurred often for each family and made my categorizations from these recollections.
I felt like family 1 was more likely to have the upper features of the face while family two was more likely to have the lower features of the face.

Family one usually always had the complete face as well as eyes and nose. Family 2 often had only one feature but sometimes more. I think family two more often had the nose and mouth the family 1. that being said I don;t think i always followed these assumptions super closely
it seemed if it wasn't obvious a face was being made, it was family 2
The full face was number 1

There seemed to be a higher likelyhood that the figure with all three options was a one.  The ones with options 2 or 3 on the bottom seemed to be more likely number 2's.  The other options seemed to vary between the two with some options being almost equally likely to be either one or two, so those were more likely to require a guess.
Single lines were option 2. Double single lines were option 2. If it had circles, it was option 1 75% of the time.
There was no strategy or pattern I used. What I did was use my memory of the previous 100 trials where I was shown which features went to each family.
I felt like the more full faces were more often in family one and the faces with only one part were more often in family 2.

There's not enough information for a complex strategy, so I take a course that may feel counterintuitive to instinct, which is to streamline the process. Single-item circles were Family 2 probably 66 percent of the time, so that's where I categorized those circles. It's hard to remind yourself to do something like that when you know that it's only part of the whole picture.

At first I was a bit confused since they all looked the same.  It wasn't until I was somewhere in the 60's of the sample set that I realized the differences.  I then realized that the full face was family 1 and that family 2 had fewer "noses" than family 1.  I think since I didn't realize the differences until later that I missed out on what I should have been looking for.  I wish I could do it over again!
I think the eyes meant family 1 because the practice looked completely random
I noticed that some features were more prevalent in one family than another. I studied those as best I could and chose between Family A and B accordingly.
I tried to learn what as most common in which family during the initial training. I realized family 1 usually had 2 or more features.
it seemed like the second "family" was usually only with one part
